21:29.705 --> 21:31.331
I don't know. Sometimes when she talks,

21:31.415 --> 21:34.126
she uses so many words
that I get a little lost.

21:34.710 --> 21:35.919
How are you feeling?

21:36.503 --> 21:37.629
Fine.

21:37.713 --> 21:39.548
Got my sweatshirt back.

21:40.716 --> 21:43.135
Are you sure you're fine?

21:46.221 --> 21:48.640
Most people I meet don't even try
to get me.

21:49.349 --> 21:51.351
Paige tried, and that was nice.

21:52.978 --> 21:54.062
That is nice.

21:55.480 --> 21:58.608
The whole time she was my girlfriend,
she bugged me.

21:58.692 --> 22:01.737
But I think I was so focused
on how annoying she is

22:01.820 --> 22:04.489
that I kind of forgot
about the good parts.

22:05.490 --> 22:06.742
That's a...

22:07.659 --> 22:09.494
great perspective, Sam.

22:10.245 --> 22:11.538
Wise beyond your years.

22:13.874 --> 22:16.293
She didn't even mind
when I locked her in my closet.

22:16.877 --> 22:18.795
That seems special and rare.

22:19.504 --> 22:20.881
Wait, what?

22:31.433 --> 22:32.601
Hey, it's me.

22:32.684 --> 22:36.271
I'm coming home, and we should talk.

22:36.897 --> 22:38.106
I love you.

22:42.819 --> 22:44.112
Apparently, I like Paige.

22:44.196 --> 22:46.073
Apparently, I like it when you knock.

22:46.156 --> 22:49.242
And now she's not my girlfriend
because of you. You drove her away.

22:49.326 --> 22:51.745
Okay, well, all you do
is complain about her.

22:52.329 --> 22:55.165
-And I get it; she's super-annoying.
-Well, I like her, I think.

22:55.290 --> 22:58.835
And you're my little sister,
and I don't need you messing with my life.

22:58.919 --> 23:01.046
Oh, my God! I was just trying to help.

23:01.421 --> 23:03.423
I'm not always gonna be around
to stick up for you.

23:03.507 --> 23:05.133
-Good.
-Sam...

23:05.217 --> 23:07.636
No, you're just like Paige.

23:07.719 --> 23:10.722
But instead of touching my books
and my turtle,

23:10.806 --> 23:14.059
you're touching my girlfriend.
I'm glad you're going to that new school,

23:14.142 --> 23:15.977
because you will not be around
to bother me.

23:16.770 --> 23:18.730
-You don't mean that.
-Yes, I do.

23:19.231 --> 23:20.399
I don't need you.

23:20.482 --> 23:23.068
-Well, good! That's what I wanted.
-Well, good!

23:28.281 --> 23:29.866
[cell phone buzzing]

23:34.955 --> 23:37.874
-Hello?
-Hey, Casey, it's Jayson...

23:37.958 --> 23:40.210
from Clayton Prep.
I just got your e-mail.

23:40.293 --> 23:42.170
Oh. Hi.

23:42.254 --> 23:43.255
You guys are prompt.

23:43.338 --> 23:45.465
[chuckles] Yeah, well...

23:45.549 --> 23:49.761
Look, I just wanted to call
to say I think you're awesome.

23:49.845 --> 23:50.679
But?

23:51.847 --> 23:52.973
But...

23:53.807 --> 23:57.727
I work at the admissions office,
and I've been hearing some people talk.

23:57.811 --> 23:58.770
You punched a girl?

24:00.480 --> 24:01.314
Oh.

24:02.065 --> 24:05.152
Yeah. But you don't know the whole story.

24:05.235 --> 24:06.945
She was bullying somebody.

24:07.028 --> 24:09.239
Okay, okay, okay, look.

24:09.322 --> 24:12.325
Write a letter to the admissions office,
and I'll do what I can.

24:12.409 --> 24:15.370
But Clayton has a zero tolerance policy
on violence.

24:15.454 --> 24:17.247
I just don't want you
to get your hopes up.

24:17.831 --> 24:19.207
I have to go.

24:26.840 --> 24:28.049
Hey, babe.

24:30.135 --> 24:31.344
Miles?

24:48.278 --> 24:53.533
And that is our youngest granddaughter,
Charlie, which is short for Charlotte.

24:53.617 --> 24:55.869
-[Doug] Cute.
-I don't know. These names lately, right?

24:55.952 --> 25:00.540
Yeah, Casey, when she was in kindergarten,
there was a child named Key.

25:00.624 --> 25:01.750
-Right.
-Yeah.

25:01.833 --> 25:04.669
-A boy or a girl?
-We weren't sure for the first few months.

25:04.753 --> 25:05.962
[laughing]

25:06.046 --> 25:09.174
But she was a girl. Cute girl, nice.
They were friends. Nice girl.

25:09.257 --> 25:11.259
-Very sweet.
-So how are your kids?

25:11.968 --> 25:13.678
-Really good.
-Yeah.

25:13.762 --> 25:16.556
Casey is getting recruited
by that school Clayton Prep.

25:16.640 --> 25:18.391
-Oh.
-For a track scholarship.

25:18.475 --> 25:20.560
Yeah, we went for a tour
the other day, on the campus.

25:20.644 --> 25:22.020
-Scholarship.
-Yeah. It'd be great.

25:22.562 --> 25:25.398
-[Donna] Exciting.
-Yeah, it's nice to spend time with Casey,

25:25.482 --> 25:28.526
'cause, you know, we're usually
so focused on Sam and so...

25:28.610 --> 25:30.737
-Why? What's going on with Sam?
-He's good.

25:30.820 --> 25:32.489
-You want more sangria?
-I'm okay.

25:32.572 --> 25:37.118
He doesn't tell me anything anymore.
Right? I have become obsolete. He's 18.

25:37.202 --> 25:38.036
[Donna] Oh.

25:38.119 --> 25:39.162
You know, so...

25:39.829 --> 25:43.250
You know, it's like girls and dating.

25:43.333 --> 25:45.043
-[Chuck] Trouble, trouble.
-Mm-hmm.

25:45.126 --> 25:46.795
-Mm-hmm.
-[Elsa] Yeah.

25:46.878 --> 25:49.798
Especially with Sam,
everything's a bit more, you know...

25:49.881 --> 25:50.966
No, what?

25:51.716 --> 25:53.051
Mm, 'cause of his autism.

25:53.134 --> 25:54.135
[Donna] What?

25:54.970 --> 25:55.804
Sam's autistic?

25:57.931 --> 25:59.140
Yeah.

26:03.395 --> 26:04.521
Um...

26:09.567 --> 26:12.487
[Elsa] You worked with Chuck
for over five years.

26:12.570 --> 26:14.197
The subject never came up?

26:14.281 --> 26:16.700
No, Chuck and I don't really
talk about that stuff.

26:17.993 --> 26:19.619
Uh-huh. I get it.

26:19.703 --> 26:20.704
You get what?

26:20.787 --> 26:22.038
It's like my friend Diego.

26:22.122 --> 26:25.083
Do you remember Diego
from when I worked with him at the salon?

26:25.166 --> 26:26.001
Yeah.

26:26.084 --> 26:29.045
It took him over a year
to tell me he was gay.

26:29.129 --> 26:31.840
He still carries a lot of shame
about his sexuality.

26:32.424 --> 26:34.593
It's a big deal for him to be out at work.

26:34.676 --> 26:37.762
Well, he works in a hair salon,
and he's not comfortable being gay?

26:37.846 --> 26:41.975
It's the same with you. You're not out
at work because you're ashamed.

26:42.058 --> 26:43.268
No, I'm not ashamed.

26:43.852 --> 26:45.520
Elsa, I'm not ashamed of anything.

26:46.271 --> 26:47.230
Okay?

26:47.314 --> 26:49.024
I just like to keep my work life

26:49.107 --> 26:51.443
and my personal life separate.
I'm not ashamed.

26:51.526 --> 26:53.862
-Mm-hmm.
-It's just how I am. It's a guy thing.

26:53.945 --> 26:56.072
Yeah, I just could never be that way,

26:56.156 --> 26:59.367
not with someone I work with every day,
someone I'm friends with.

26:59.451 --> 27:01.077
It's a huge part of my identity.

27:01.161 --> 27:03.121
-Yeah, but maybe it shouldn't be.
-What?

27:03.204 --> 27:06.207
Everything with you revolves
around being a mom.

27:06.291 --> 27:10.003
And maybe sometime you should just,
you know, be like an individual person.

27:10.086 --> 27:12.088
I am an individual person.

27:12.172 --> 27:13.423
No, I don't think you are.

27:13.798 --> 27:15.884
Everything is Sam this and autism that.

27:15.967 --> 27:18.428
Maybe it's time to step back
and have your own life.

27:23.058 --> 27:26.019
It takes me a while
to get used to new things.

27:26.102 --> 27:28.396
But once I get used to something,

27:29.105 --> 27:30.273
I come to rely on it.

27:37.405 --> 27:40.075
[woman speaking French]

27:41.201 --> 27:42.118
Paige?

27:42.202 --> 27:44.162
[in French]  Pardon, monsieur...

27:44.245 --> 27:46.956
-Sam, what are you doing here?
-En Français.

27:47.707 --> 27:50.251
